","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null},{"team_id":null,"role_name":"Course Designer","team_name":null,"individual_id":"019d0a11-4d30-76ee-9a0d-1d875a72b54f","citation_count":1,"individual_name":"Peteris Ledins","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null},{"team_id":null,"role_name":"Epunch Coordinator","team_name":null,"individual_id":"019d0a11-4d2f-78a9-8722-6f8ceafbfa42","citation_count":1,"individual_name":"Gina Nuss","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null},{"team_id":null,"role_name":"Meet Director","team_name":null,"individual_id":"01913919-da03-757e-b829-aa2bdc684400","citation_count":1,"individual_name":"Debbie Newell","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null}],"organizing_club_id":"01912f3e-e3e1-7e8e-b3c6-32387a8b4990","result_source_brief":"CascadeOC Website: https://www.cascadeoc.org/result/ultimate-series-2-long/","organizing_club_name":"Cascade Orienteering Club","cumulative_event_comments":"Ultimate Series #1 – Middle – Frenchman Coulee\n\nWineries – while there are several in the area, most are closed at this time of year; an exception is Cave B Winery and Resort\nBased on feedback from our vetters (Eric Bone was there 2/17 and Gabe Svobodny 2/19), we have shortened the courses for both days. Eric reported some snow on the ground, with drifts shin- to knee-deep, and a few spots near cliff bases thigh-deep. The warmer weather melted some of the snow by the time Gabe visited two days later. Even if more melts by this weekend, conditions could be mostly slow mud.\nThe traffic camera on I-90 at Exit 143 represents pretty closely the conditions at the event site.\nAlso, if you’re coming from Western Washington, please be sure to check conditions in the passes before heading over.\nDesert Runs\nWe’re opening the 2017 Ultimate Orienteer Series with a collaboration between Forest Runs and Cascade for a 2-day event in eastern Washington. We’ll be using Forest Runs’ excellent map of Frenchman Coulee near Vantage, WA for Middle (Saturday) and Long (Sunday) events.\nWeather\nOut of Bounds areas\nPrivate property, areas of cultural significance, or dangerous slopes are marked on the map as out of bounds. There are no markings in the terrain, so please pay attention to where you are. One slope is marked on the map, as it might be tempting to cross it, but that would be both slippery and dangerous due to falling rocks.\nSpectator location\nAfter you’ve finished, if weather permits, the second-last control is a good place to view and cheer on your fellow competitors.\n\nWineries – while there are several in the area, most are closed at this time of year; an exception is Cave B Winery and Resort\nBased on feedback from our vetters (Eric Bone was there 2/17 and Gabe Svobodny 2/19), we have shortened the courses for both days. Eric reported some snow on the ground, with drifts shin- to knee-deep, and a few spots near cliff bases thigh-deep. The warmer weather melted some of the snow by the time Gabe visited two days later. Even if more melts by this weekend, conditions could be mostly slow mud.\nThe traffic camera on I-90 at Exit 143 represents pretty closely the conditions at the event site.\nAlso, if you’re coming from Western Washington, please be sure to check conditions in the passes before heading over.\nWe’re opening the 2017 Ultimate Orienteer Series with a collaboration between Forest Runs and Cascade for a 2-day event in eastern Washington. We’ll be using Forest Runs’ excellent map of Frenchman Coulee near Vantage, WA for Middle (Saturday) and Long (Sunday) events.\nTemperatures are expected to be above freezing during the day and below freezing at night, with little to no snow. There’s a WSDOT traffic camera near Vantage that you can check for snow cover.\nThe map terrain and surrounding areas are unique and beautiful. Below are some other things to explore nearby.\nOut of Bounds areas\nPrivate property, areas of cultural significance, or dangerous slopes are marked on the map as out of bounds. There are no markings in the terrain, so please pay attention to where you are. One slope is marked on the map, as it might be tempting to cross it, but that would be both slippery and dangerous due to falling rocks.\nSpectator location\nAfter you’ve finished, if weather permits, the second-last control is a good place to view and cheer on your fellow competitors.\n\nQuestions or changes, contact: epunch@cascadeoc.org"}
